{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 14:02:33.211299", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\\n\\nScope and objectives\\n- Detect anomalies in connectivity.\\n- Localize faulty device(s).\\n- Identify root cause based on observed data.\\n- No remediation is proposed at this stage.\\n\\nHigh-level network health\\n- Control plane (OSPF): Healthy. Distribution routers have full OSPF adjacencies to core, and the server_access_router has OSPF routes to both access subnets and the server farm:\\n  - server_access_router: OSPF to 10.1.1.0/24 and 10.2.1.0/24 via core; 10.200.0.0/24 directly connected.\\n  - router_dist_2_1: OSPF neighbor Full/Backup on eth0; routes to 10.200.0.0/24 via core; 10.2.1.0/24 connected via br0.\\n  - router_dist_1_1: OSPF neighbor Full/Backup on eth0; routes as expected.\\n- Server farm reachability: From host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.10), DNS (10.200.0.2) and the load balancer (10.200.0.7) are reachable. HTTP to web99.local and to web_server_0 (web0.local / 10.200.0.3) succeeds with typical RTTs and TTFB variations consistent with application behavior.\\n- Access switching: Access switches are up, bridging correctly (br0 active with eth uplinks). No link errors observed.\\n\\nDetected anomalies\\n1) Host host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10) has no L3 connectivity:\\n   - host_2_1_1_1 → DNS 10.200.0.2: ping timed out.\\n   - host_2_1_1_1 → default gateway 10.2.1.1: ping timed out.\\n   - router_dist_2_1 → host_2_1_1_1: ping timed out.\\n   - server_access_router → host_2_1_1_1: ping timed out.\\n\\n2) ARP/Neighbor table inconsistency on host_2_1_1_1:\\n   - host_2_1_1_1 “ip neigh show dev eth0” shows:\\n     - 10.2.1.1 lladdr 00:11:22:33:44:55 PERMANENT\\n     This is a static/permanent neighbor entry pointing the default gateway IP to a fake/nonexistent MAC.\\n   - router_dist_2_1 “ip neigh show dev br0” shows:\\n     - 10.2.1.10 lladdr fe:22:19:82:37:27 REACHABLE\\n     This matches host_2’s NIC MAC and indicates the router can resolve the host at L2.\\n   - router_dist_2_1’s br0 MAC is b6:15:53:7f:29:18 (per interface info), which does not match the host’s permanent neighbor entry.\\n\\n3) DHCP and local link status for host_2_1_1_1 are normal:\\n   - Interface eth0 up, link detected at 10Gb/s.\\n   - IP obtained via DHCP: 10.2.1.10/24 with default route via 10.2.1.1 and nameserver 10.200.0.2.\\n   - Access switch and distribution router ports are up with normal counters.\\n\\nImpact assessment\\n- host_2_1_1_1 cannot communicate beyond its local interface. It cannot reach its default gateway, DNS, or server farm. Inbound pings from the distribution router also fail (no replies).\\n- Other parts of the network (host_1_1_1_1 and server farm) operate normally; OSPF control plane is converged and stable.\\n\\nFault localization\\n- The failure is isolated to host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10). All upstream devices (access switch, distribution router, core, server_access_router, servers, and OSPF) function correctly.\\n\\nRoot cause analysis\\n- Misconfigured static ARP/neigh entry on host_2_1_1_1 for the default gateway IP 10.2.1.1:\\n  - Host has a PERMANENT neighbor entry mapping 10.2.1.1 to 00:11:22:33:44:55.\\n  - The actual router MAC on that segment is b6:15:53:7f:29:18 (router_dist_2_1 br0).\\n  - Consequence:\\n    - Packets from host_2_1_1_1 destined to 10.2.1.1 are sent to a nonexistent MAC and are blackholed on the L2 segment.\\n    - Pings initiated by the router to the host do reach the host (router has correct ARP for the host), but the host’s replies to the router IP are sent to the wrong MAC and never reach the router, causing ping timeouts.\\n- This explains both directions of the observed connectivity failures and aligns with all measurements.\\n\\nAdditional observations\\n- DNS configuration on both hosts points to 10.200.0.2 and is correct.\\n- HTTP from host_1_1_1_1 to the load balancer and web servers shows normal name resolution and acceptable performance; no indication of routing asymmetry or path loss in that path.\\n- The design constraint that backend web servers (behind the load balancer) are not directly reachable from hosts is not contradicted by the tests performed; only front-end web servers/web99 were accessed as intended.\\n\\nSummary\\n- Anomaly: Host 10.2.1.10 has complete L3 outage.\\n- Localization: The issue is local to host_2_1_1_1’s neighbor table.\\n- Root cause: Incorrect permanent ARP/neighbor entry for 10.2.1.1 on host_2_1_1_1 (mapped to 00:11:22:33:44:55 instead of the router’s MAC b6:15:53:7f:29:18), causing all traffic to the default gateway to be sent to an invalid MAC and dropping replies to router-originated traffic., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='82942292-6f93-4728-bc98-51e1a903d653'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
